# Ultimate Stabilization of Bento Grid Border Light

The current implementation using large rotating gradients is causing persistent viewport-wide light bleed artifacts and lingering performance overhead. I will switch to a localized light source approach (Vercel-style) which is 100% stable and high-performance.

## Proposed Changes

### Component: [BorderBeam.tsx](file:///c:/Users/Admin/Desktop/prod-2-adecos/src/components/ui/border-beam.tsx)

#### [MODIFY] [BorderBeam.tsx](file:///c:/Users/Admin/Desktop/prod-2-adecos/src/components/ui/border-beam.tsx)
- **Localized Light Source:** Replace the large rotating gradient with a single small `<motion.div>` (approx. 200px wide).
- **Precision Pathing:** Use `offsetPath: "inset(0 round 24px)"` to move this localized light precisely along the border.
- **Hardware Shading:** Create the "glow" using standard CSS `box-shadow` and `linear-gradient` on this small div.
- **Zero Bleed:** Since the light source is small and confined to the path, it is physically impossible for it to bleed to the viewport margins.

### Component: [BentoGrid.tsx](file:///c:/Users/Admin/Desktop/prod-2-adecos/src/components/BentoGrid.tsx)
- Keep the current structure (Inner wrapper for padding). This ensures the `offset-path` (inset 0) stays perfectly flush with the box borders.

## Why this will resolve the issue
- **Previous Mismatch Fix:** The earlier "mismatch" was caused by the parent's internal padding. With the new inner wrapper structure, `offsetPath: inset(0)` will now match the border line with 100% precision.
- **Bleed Fix:** Large rotating elements often cause rendering glitches in hardware-accelerated layers. A small, moving div is the industry standard for this effect and is 100% stable.

## Verification Plan
- **Performance:** Verify stable 60fps.
- **Bleed Check:** Confirm ABSOLUTELY ZERO blue light at screen margins.
- **Alignment:** Verify the 200px light beam is flush with all 4 borders.
